commit.message:
Skip customXml in docx

Users can include arbitrary XML here, not visible in the document,
Some use it to add tags like "this document should be archived"; stuff
that should probably not be translated. Sometimes apertium even gives
invalid xml here, which leads to scary warnings on opening the docx.

Let `tf-extract` be passed -H when -H passed to `apertium` script

cf.
https://github.com/TinoDidriksen/Transfuse/issues/15
Fix utfcpp 4.x build failure (fixes #193)

Allow inverting preference values with initial minus

If preferences.xml has

  <preference id="ise_ize">
    <description lang="eng">Use -ize instead of -ise</description>
    <options>
      <option id="agonise"/>
      <option id="idolise"/>
      <option id="exorcise"/>
      <option id="lionise"/>
    </options>

and user does

    export AP_SETVAR="ise_ize=-agonise:idolise,color_colour"

then that will now be equivalent to

    export AP_SETVAR="ise_ize=exorcise:lionise,color_colour"

Very handy when list of options is a bit long and user wants to turn
off the preference for a single word.

Uses the preferences xml from "$DATADIR/prefs/$PAIR.xml" (if it can't
find that, tries to fall back by removing everything after last dash
in mode name if it can't find that, so debug modes should be supported
as well).

Don't allow shifting past empty input buffer

will hang

cf. #194

Implement <reject-current-rule shifting="N"/>

where N is a pattern-item position; this lets us use it for lookahead
on rules of more than two pattern-items:

    <rule comment="transpose word 3 and 4; lookahead on word 5">
      <pattern>
        <pattern-item n="pasvsubj"/>    <!-- den -->
        <pattern-item n="aux"/>         <!-- blir -->
        <pattern-item n="pasv-pp"/>     <!-- driven-->
        <pattern-item n="adv_unbound"/> <!-- i dag -->
        <pattern-item n="prep"/>        <!-- Ensure following preposition -->
      </pattern>
      <action>
        <out>
          <chunk><clip pos="1" part="whole"/></chunk> <b/> <!-- den -->
          <chunk><clip pos="2" part="whole"/></chunk> <b/> <!-- blir -->
          <chunk><clip pos="4" part="whole"/></chunk> <b/> <!-- i dag -->
          <chunk><clip pos="3" part="whole"/></chunk> <b/> <!-- driven -->
        </out>
        <reject-current-rule shifting="4"/>
      </action>
    </rule>

Fixes #194
std::unary_function no longer exists

commit.message:
Precompile def-cats

This shifts rule transducer growth from exponential to linear, causing
a very slight increase in overhead for very small files (whose
compilation time was negligible to begin with) and having an
increasing effect as the number of rules and particularly the length
of the patterns increases.

| file         | old      | new     | improvement |
|--------------|----------|---------|-------------|
| eng-spa.t1x  |   147 MB | 16.5 MB |          9x |
|              |   2.87 s |   0.25s |         11x |
| nob-nno.t1x  |   155 MB | 16.7 MB |          9x |
|              |  3.267 s | 0.081 s |         40x |
| oci-fra.t2bx |  2655 MB | 15.7 KB |        168x |
|              | 310.98 s | 0.045 s |       6909x |

The downside of this is that we can no longer report when rules using
different def-cats have overlapping paths, though this can be checked
by apertium-lint, so it's not a huge loss.

commit.message:
Capitalization Post-processor (#170)

Adds the following programs:

apertium-extract-caps
copies capitalization information from surface form and analysis to word-bound blank

apertium-compile-caps
compiles an XML file of capitalization rules to an FST

apertium-restore-caps
uses the wblanks from -extract-caps and the rules from -compile-caps to determine the best capitalization of each input word

Full documentation at https://wiki.apertium.org/wiki/Capitalization_restoration

commit.message:
configure.ac: fix bashism

configure scripts need to be runnable with a POSIX-compliant /bin/sh.

On many (but not all!) systems, /bin/sh is provided by Bash, so errors
like this aren't spotted. Notably Debian defaults to /bin/sh provided
by dash which doesn't tolerate such bashisms as '=='.

This retains compatibility with bash.

Signed-off-by: Sam James <sam@gentoo.org>
